emination of Architectural Knowledge in Brazilian Favelas -- t10 Towards Belonging: Informal Design and Dwelling Practices in Northern Colombia -- t11 (Re)Building the City of Medellín: Beyond State Rhetoric vs. Personal Experience – A Call for Consolidated Synergies -- tPart V Reflections -- t12 Home and Belonging: Reflections from Urban Mexico -- t13 One Block at a Time: Performing the Neighbourhood -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe intricacies of living in contemporary Latin American cities include cases of both empowerment and restriction. In Lima, residents built their own homes and formed community organizations, while in Rio de Janeiro inhabitants of the favelas needed to be “pacified” in anticipation of international sporting events. Aspirations to “get ahead in life” abound in the region, but so do multiple limitations to realizing the dream of upward mobility. This volume captures the paradoxical histories and experiences of urban life in Latin America, offering new empirical and theoretical insights to scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCity planningzLatin America. 0aHousingzLatin America. 0aUrban policyzLatin America. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh1 aDohnke, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGelder, Jean-Louis Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrajeda, Erika Denisse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHordijk, Michaela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHölzl, Corinna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInclán-Valadez, Cristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel